blog.title: "I'm just an empty void waiting to be filled"...

summary:
“I know everything I need to know about you," she countered, taken aback. "You
 do?" he asked, and peered at her, eyes intent....
caption:
“I know everything I need to know about you,“ she countered, taken aback.
"You do?” he asked, and peered at her, eyes intent. “You do, You have that look in your eyes from the forest, when you called me a monster.”
He came within a meter or two of Rey, and she wondered what would happen if she refused to move and they intersected. Would she find herself in his mind again, and have to endure his presence in hers? Could they actually touch, across a galaxy?
“You are a monster,” Rey said, remembering the terror of her paralysis on Takodana.
She stared back at him – and found his.eyes full of hurt. Hurt – and conflict.
“Yes, I am,” Kylo said, and there was no menace in his voice – only misery.”  


 ― Jason Fry, The Last Jedi: Expanded Edition (Exclusive Edition)

summary: (Not the continuation of last week's, as I only have half of that one's direction chosen. Instead, it's one of my older ones...
body:
Fic Prompts: Star Wars Wednesday

(Not the continuation of last week’s, as I only have half of that one’s direction chosen. Instead, it’s one of my older ones from deviantart, plus the picture that went with it)

Luke stopped and tilted his head to the side. In the center of the chamber their hostess had set aside for princess Leia’s personal use, the long – and frankly rather horrible – tassel curtains had been removed from the window and were in the process of being braided together. Princess Leia knelt on the thick carpet, seemingly intent on her work, but at Luke’s pause, she glanced up.

“Go on, I’m listening,” she said.

She was still wearing the simple but elegant gown their hostess had loaned her – it had evidently belonged to the countess herself in her youth, and as a matter of mostly harmless vanity she wished to see the last princess of Alderaan in it – and she’d added a decorative short cape to the ensemble to more easily conceal a small blast pistol at the back of her belt. Somehow this, added to her busy hands flying over the tassels as though braiding her own hair, lent an unusually fairytale aura to her that surprised Luke.

“Princess, I’ve been giving this whole situation some thought and something just seems off. I don’t know if it’s the Force warning me about something…I’m still figuring out how that works…or if I’m just uncomfortable because I don’t really understand politics-”

“Er, sorry,” he mumbled when he realized he’d probably been staring, “It’s just…um, what exactly are you doing, Princess?”

Leia grinned sharply and stood with a rustle of cloth. “C'mere and I’ll show you.”

Luke gingerly crossed the lavish room. He and the other pilots sent to escort Princess Leia on this mission had been placed in quarters several floors below in the castle, where the rooms were far simpler and more obviously meant for employees or servants. Luke felt distinctly out of place in the luxurious tower chambers the hostess had placed the higher ranked members of the Alliance in.

His boots, worn and secondhand but neatly polished, sank into the carpet, which looked softer than most beds he’d known. He moved slowly, as though afraid he’d soil the gleaming white fabric beneath his feet if he walked faster. The stone walls and the wide bed were all decorated with the colors of Alderaan’s royal house.

Luke wasn’t sure if that was a touching gesture or shockingly poor taste.

Leia handed him one end of the loose braid of burgundy cloth and instructed him to secure it to a wall sconce that was just slightly out of her reach.

“I think your instincts are probably right,” the princess said conversationally, “Countess Dulinne has a legitimate reason for wanting to support the Alliance: her husband was killed in the Clone Wars by a Republic raid gone wrong, and her only son was shot by the Empire as a deserter last year, though it was pretty obvious the charges were false. Nevertheless, she’s definitely after something besides our protection in exchange for her wealth.”

She tossed the other end of the tassel rope out the open window and watched with a gleam in her eye as it tumbled down over the warm stone walls. “We’re probably being monitored, of course, that’s just prudent. If the doors are being watched, this will be a quicker way to the Countess’s study. I’d like a word with her away from her bodyguards and sycophants.”

Leia paused as if considering something, then added, “Or, if she isn’t in, I’ll do a little reconnaissance to make sure she’s telling the truth.”

Luke blanched. “You’re not suggesting – but you’re not really going to – are you kidding me?”

This was risky business, poking about in a potential ally’s – a wealthy potential ally at that – private study. Aside from that, Luke’s only real qualm was that the whole affair was so frightfully like something out of the children’s tales from Naboo he’d been reading lately that he half expected someone to call up to Leia to let down her hair at any moment, or a strange little being to appear, offering to spin straw into credits.

“Relax, Luke,” Leia snorted. She gathered her skirts and eased over the sill. “I used to do this all the time when I was a kid.”

Somehow, that didn’t surprise Luke nearly as much as he thought it ought to have. 

“What if someone asks after you while you’re…um…out?” he asked, tugging experimentally on the rope to ensure that the knot held.

Leia gestured towards the door. “If the corridors are monitored like I think, just slip out the door and say something like ‘Goodnight’ or 'I won’t disturb you’ to make it sound like I’m resting. Then if anyone asks you, tell them that as far as you know, I’m in my chamber." 

With that she took hold of the rope and began to rappel down. 

"Oh, and Luke,” she called up when she was perhaps a meter below the window, “I’d be careful about showing that lightsaber to anyone. I’ve heard rumors that the Countess Dulinne is a collector of Clone Wars memorabilia. Not to say we’d have another Grakkus incident, but you never know how she might react.”

Luke shuddered and did his best to shove away the memories of being a prisoner on the smugglers’ moon. He’d learned some useful things about lightsaber combat there, but nearly being enslaved by a Hutt and killed by a monster in the arena sort of took all the fun out of it. 

“Right,” he sighed, “I’ll go see if the guys have heard anything in the meantime, unless Commander Narra needs me to do anything." 

"Don’t tell him what I’m up to, he’ll have kittens,” Leia said in a very matter-of-fact way, then slipped out of sight. 

Luke decided then that it was a good thing the Princess hadn’t grown up on Tatooine, like he had. She was just reckless enough that if they’d known each other as children, he suspected they’d have gotten into even more trouble than he and Biggs had.

Fic Prompts: Star Wars Wednesday

(Not the continuation of last week’s, as I only have half of that one’s direction chosen. Instead, it’s one of my older ones from deviantart, plus the picture that went with it)

Luke stopped and tilted his head to the side. In the center of the chamber their hostess had set aside for princess Leia’s personal use, the long – and frankly rather horrible – tassel curtains had been removed from the window and were in the process of being braided together. Princess Leia knelt on the thick carpet, seemingly intent on her work, but at Luke’s pause, she glanced up.

“Go on, I’m listening,” she said.

[[MORE]]

She was still wearing the simple but elegant gown their hostess had loaned her – it had evidently belonged to the countess herself in her youth, and as a matter of mostly harmless vanity she wished to see the last princess of Alderaan in it – and she’d added a decorative short cape to the ensemble to more easily conceal a small blast pistol at the back of her belt. Somehow this, added to her busy hands flying over the tassels as though braiding her own hair, lent an unusually fairytale aura to her that surprised Luke.

“Princess, I’ve been giving this whole situation some thought and something just seems off. I don’t know if it’s the Force warning me about something…I’m still figuring out how that works…or if I’m just uncomfortable because I don’t really understand politics-”

“Er, sorry,” he mumbled when he realized he’d probably been staring, “It’s just…um, what exactly are you doing, Princess?”

Leia grinned sharply and stood with a rustle of cloth. “C'mere and I’ll show you.”

Luke gingerly crossed the lavish room. He and the other pilots sent to escort Princess Leia on this mission had been placed in quarters several floors below in the castle, where the rooms were far simpler and more obviously meant for employees or servants. Luke felt distinctly out of place in the luxurious tower chambers the hostess had placed the higher ranked members of the Alliance in.

His boots, worn and secondhand but neatly polished, sank into the carpet, which looked softer than most beds he’d known. He moved slowly, as though afraid he’d soil the gleaming white fabric beneath his feet if he walked faster. The stone walls and the wide bed were all decorated with the colors of Alderaan’s royal house.

Luke wasn’t sure if that was a touching gesture or shockingly poor taste.

Leia handed him one end of the loose braid of burgundy cloth and instructed him to secure it to a wall sconce that was just slightly out of her reach.

“I think your instincts are probably right,” the princess said conversationally, “Countess Dulinne has a legitimate reason for wanting to support the Alliance: her husband was killed in the Clone Wars by a Republic raid gone wrong, and her only son was shot by the Empire as a deserter last year, though it was pretty obvious the charges were false. Nevertheless, she’s definitely after something besides our protection in exchange for her wealth.”

She tossed the other end of the tassel rope out the open window and watched with a gleam in her eye as it tumbled down over the warm stone walls. “We’re probably being monitored, of course, that’s just prudent. If the doors are being watched, this will be a quicker way to the Countess’s study. I’d like a word with her away from her bodyguards and sycophants.”

Leia paused as if considering something, then added, “Or, if she isn’t in, I’ll do a little reconnaissance to make sure she’s telling the truth.”

Luke blanched. “You’re not suggesting – but you’re not really going to – are you kidding me?”

This was risky business, poking about in a potential ally’s – a wealthy potential ally at that – private study. Aside from that, Luke’s only real qualm was that the whole affair was so frightfully like something out of the children’s tales from Naboo he’d been reading lately that he half expected someone to call up to Leia to let down her hair at any moment, or a strange little being to appear, offering to spin straw into credits.

“Relax, Luke,” Leia snorted. She gathered her skirts and eased over the sill. “I used to do this all the time when I was a kid.”

Somehow, that didn’t surprise Luke nearly as much as he thought it ought to have. 

“What if someone asks after you while you’re…um…out?” he asked, tugging experimentally on the rope to ensure that the knot held.

Leia gestured towards the door. “If the corridors are monitored like I think, just slip out the door and say something like ‘Goodnight’ or 'I won’t disturb you’ to make it sound like I’m resting. Then if anyone asks you, tell them that as far as you know, I’m in my chamber." 

With that she took hold of the rope and began to rappel down. 

"Oh, and Luke,” she called up when she was perhaps a meter below the window, “I’d be careful about showing that lightsaber to anyone. I’ve heard rumors that the Countess Dulinne is a collector of Clone Wars memorabilia. Not to say we’d have another Grakkus incident, but you never know how she might react.”

Luke shuddered and did his best to shove away the memories of being a prisoner on the smugglers’ moon. He’d learned some useful things about lightsaber combat there, but nearly being enslaved by a Hutt and killed by a monster in the arena sort of took all the fun out of it. 

“Right,” he sighed, “I’ll go see if the guys have heard anything in the meantime, unless Commander Narra needs me to do anything." 

"Don’t tell him what I’m up to, he’ll have kittens,” Leia said in a very matter-of-fact way, then slipped out of sight. 

Luke decided then that it was a good thing the Princess hadn’t grown up on Tatooine, like he had. She was just reckless enough that if they’d known each other as children, he suspected they’d have gotten into even more trouble than he and Biggs had.
